Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity
Description:
An Activity is an identification of the occurrence of an action that has taken place, is taking place, or is expected to take place in the future. The procedure executed during that Activity is identified with the ActivityMethod that is referred to by the chosenMethod attribute.

EXAMPLE 1   Change, distilling, design, a process to drill a hole, and a task such as training someone, are examples of activities.

NOTE 1   The items that are affected by an Activity, for example as input or output, may be identified within an instance of ActivityAssignment.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.activityType
Description:

the activityType specifies the purpose of the Activity.

The following values shall be used for activityType:

  • 'amendment': An Activity to add information to product data;
  • 'analysis': An Activity to determine the behaviour of an element under certain physical circumstances;
  • 'cancellation': An Activity to delete an element from the bill of material or to cancel the whole bill of material;
  • 'delivery change': An Activity to change the delivery schedule of an element;
  • 'design change': An Activity to change the design of an item or an assembly; this might include changes to the geometry or to properties of the object;
  • 'design': An Activity concerning the development of a design of an item;
  • 'mock-up creation': An Activity to create an experimental model or replica of an item;
  • 'prototype building': An Activity to manufacture a preliminary version of an item;
  • 'rectification': An Activity to correct the data, documentation or structure associated with an item;
  • 'restructuring': An Activity to create a new structure or position within a bill of material without changing the data associated with the items in the bill of material;
  • 'spare part creation': An Activity to design a spare part or to classify an item as a spare part;
  • 'stop notice': An Activity to stop the manufacturing process of an item;
  • 'testing': An Activity to test an item;
  • 'work definition': An Activity to manage several sub-activities related to this Activity by an ActivityRelationship with a relationType of value 'decomposition'.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.actualEndDate
Description:

the date when the Activity actually finished. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.actualStartDate
Description:

the date when the Activity actually started. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.chosenMethod
Description:

the ActivityMethod that specifies the procedure selected to carry out the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.concernedOrganizations
Description:

the set of Organization objects that are affected by the result of the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.plannedEndDate
Description:

the date when the Activity is or was supposed to be finished. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.plannedStartDate
Description:

the date when the Activity is or was supposed to be started. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.requestor
Description:

the Person or Organization that requested the Activity and the date the request was submitted. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.resolvedRequests
Description:

the set of WorkRequest objects that are resolved by the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.status
Description:

the status specifies the level of completion of the Activity. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

EXAMPLE 2   The value 'open' is an example for status.

NOTE 3   The values and sequence of status are company specific.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.supplyingOrganizations
Description:

the set of Organization objects that carry out the work. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Activity.authorization
Description:

the WorkOrder object that controls the Activity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment
Description:
An ActivityAssignment is a an association of an Activity with product or activity data. It characterizes the role of the concepts represented with these data with respect to the activity.

NOTE 1   This entity should not be used to represent the association of an activity with the organizations that are responsible for its execution or its management. That kind of information can be represented with instances of OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the ActivityAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ActivityAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the ActivityAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment.role
Description:

the meaning of the assignment/association. Where applicable, the following values shall be used:

  • 'input': the concepts represented by the items are inputs of the Activity;
  • 'output': the concepts represented by the items result from the Activity;
  • 'constraint': the concepts represented by the items influence the execution of the Activity.

    • EXAMPLE 1   Presence of a gas tube may constrain the execution of drilling of a hole.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment.assignedActivity
Description:

the Activity that is considered.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityAssignment.assignedTo
Description:

the set of ActivityAssignmentSelect that are associated with the assignedActivity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethod
Description:
An ActivityMethod is a way to carry out an Activity.

NOTE 1   There may be more than one method for producing a required result.

NOTE 2   This definition may be used to characterize a way to resolve a request for action.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethod.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the ActivityMethod. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethod.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the ActivityMethod is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethod.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ActivityMethod. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Description:

the text that provides an informal description of the reason for the ActivityMethod.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodRelationship
Description:
A ActivityMethodRelationship is a relationship between two instances of ActivityMethod.

Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ActivityMethodRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodRelationship.related
Description:

the other object of ActivityMethod that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodRelationship.wr:WR1
Description:

the relating ActivityMethod and the related ActivityMethod must be different.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation
Description:
An ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation is an association between an ActivityMethod and a WorkRequest. The associated ActivityMethod serves as a recommended or non-recommended method to resolve the tasks specified in the WorkRequest. The associationType attribute characterizes the meaning of that association and the meaning of the ActivityMethod with respect to the WorkRequest.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation.associationType
Description:

the associationType specifies whether the specified ActivityMethod may be used or not. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'non recommended method': The specified ActivityMethod shall not be used in order to accomplish the specified WorkRequest,
  • 'recommended method': The specified ActivityMethod may be used in order to accomplish the specified WorkRequest.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation.associatedActivityMethod
Description:

the associatedActivityMethod identifies the ActivityMethod that is recommended or that shall not be chosen.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityMethodWorkRequestAssociation.associatedWorkRequest
Description:

the associatedWorkRequest identifies the WorkRequest that the recommended or non-recommended method applies to.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship
Description:

An ActivityRelationship is a relationship between two Activity objects.

EXAMPLE 1   The activity required to complete a work order, may be decomposed into a series of activities. Their corresponding instances would be related using instances of the ActivityRelationship entity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ActivityRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the ActivityRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'alternative': The application object defines a relationship where the related Activity may be used alternatively instead of the relating Activity;
  • 'decomposition': The application object defines a relationship where the related Activity is one of potentially more sub-activities into which the relating Activity is broken down;
  • 'derivation': The application object defines a relationship where the related Activity is derived from the relating Activity;

    EXAMPLE 2   An Activity that is controlled by a WorkOrder with orderType 'manufacturing release' may be derived from (is based on) another Activity controlled by another WorkOrder with orderType 'design release'..

  • 'exclusiveness': The application object defines a relationship where the relating and the related Activity shall not have any overlap in time of execution;
  • 'precedence': The application object defines a relationship where the related Activity has higher priority than the relating Activity;
  • 'sequence': The application object defines a relationship where the relating Activity shall be completed before the related Activity starts;
  • 'simultaneity': The application object defines a relationship that establishes that both the relating and related Activity are considered as occurring during the same time period or shall be performed together in order to ensure consistency and enhance efficiency.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship.relating
Description:

one object of Activity that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The relating usually identifies the Activity, which is based on the definition of the related, for example, derived from or dependent on.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship.related
Description:

the other object of Activity that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   The related usually identifies the Activity, which is based on the definition of the relating.

NOTE 4   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ActivityRelationship.wr:WR1
Description:

the related Activity and the relating Activity must be different.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.AlternatePartRelationship
Description:

A AlternatePartRelationship is a type of PartRelationship where the relating part represents the base part and the related part represents the alternate part.

It specifies that any version of the alternate part, may be used in place of any version of the base part, regardless of its usages and of its versions. The relationship established by the AlternatePartRelationship is not symmetric: if part B is an alternate part for part A, part A is not implied to be an alternate part for part B.

NOTE 1   If a part is an alternate for another part, it is understood that there is no interest in keeping track of which part, the base or any alternates specified, is used as a particular instance of the base part within a part structure

NOTE 2   An organization may track design changes for a base part, and establish effectivity conditions for the use of that base part in various assemblies to be manufactured. The use of an alternate part implies that an organization does not specify any particular version of the alternate part nor establish effectivities relating to it

NOTE 3   An AlternatePartRelationship may relate parts of any kind, provided both related Part objects identify parts of the same part category.

NOTE 4   An AlternatePartRelationship for which the base part is an assembly involves that the entire part structure of the alternate part may be used in place of the base part and its part structure.

NOTE 5   This concept usually refers to form, fit, function, and quality. Additional properties such as performance, noise, endurance, or reliability may also be considered as a prerequisite for the replacement

EXAMPLE    Two bolts of the same size are parts. One bolt has a square head and the other has a hexagonal head. The two bolts are considered equivalent with respect to form, fit, and function: they both have sufficiently close physical shape, they take up the same space when used, and they both serve to fasten two things together. Thus, one of these two bolts could be considered to be an alternate part for the other bolt.

NOTE 6   The following additional data can be assigned to an AlternatePartRelationship: Approval, Certification, DateTimeString, InformationUsageRight, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.AlternatePartRelationship.criteria
Description:

the word or set of words describing the requirements that are covered by both the base part and the alternate part and therefore are the basis for the statement regarding the capability of replacing the base part by the alternate part.

NOTE 7   Additional properties such as performance, noise, endurance, or reliability may also be considered as a prerequisite for the replacement in addition to form, fit, function, and quality.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.AlternatePartRelationship.relationType
Description:

the inherited attribute relationType. The value of relationType shall be 'alternate'.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.AlternatePartRelationship.ur:UR1
Description:

The combination of the related part and the relating part shall be unique.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.BeveledSheetRepresentation
Description:
A BeveledSheetRepresentation is a type of ConstituentShapeRepresentation that has a significant thickness, and whose edge is beveled at a constant angle around its entire perimeter. It is an extension of the concept of a thin sheet to products, such as honeycomb core, that have significant thickness but can be formed to mate with a curved surface.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.BeveledSheetRepresentation.bevelAngle
Description:
specifies the angle from the plane normal to the defining surface of part's profile to the beveled surface.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.BeveledSheetRepresentation.boundarySurface
Description:
specifies the base exterior boundary and defining surface of the part.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.BeveledSheetRepresentation.verticalProfileHeight
Description:
specifies the vertical height of the part's profile from the base boundary to where the bevel begins.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.BeveledSheetRepresentation.wr:WR1
Description:
ensure that the units for angle and length are correct.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.BoundaryCurveRepresentation
Description:
A BoundaryCurveRepresentation is a set of curves that define the sheet edge. These curves define a closed area but are not necessarily restrained topologically. The curves that encompass the other curves are the outer boundary, while curves that define a closed area within the outer boundary are cutouts.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CentreOfMass
Description:

A CentreOfMass is a type of ShapeDependentProperty that is the centre of the mass of a body. The relative position of the CentreOfMass within the body is an invariant datum relative to rotation and translation. The CentreOfMass is a characteristic of a part, not its shape.

NOTE 1   If a shape representation is present, the CentreOfMass is usually derivable from the shape representation. However, as a characteristic of a part, it may be pre-defined in order to reflect a requirement.

NOTE 2   In order to convey the information about the actual centre of mass of a geometric model, the use of GeneralShapeDependentProperty with value 'centroid' for its attribute propertyType is appropriate.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CentreOfMass.centrePoint
Description:
a point in three-dimensional space that defines the location of a CentreOfMass in the GeometricCoordinateSpace.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CentreOfMass.definedIn
Description:

the GeometricCoordinateSpace in which the property is applicable.

NOTE 3   The values of geometry related properties are specified relative to a GeometricCoordinateSpace.

EXAMPLE    A CentreOfMass may be specified in different coordinate spaces for different dimensioning applications.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Class
Description:

A Class is a classification of an object which characterizes all objects of the same kind; such a classification is independent from the application of the classified object.

EXAMPLE 1   A fastener with subclasses, such as fastener with 2 or 3 fixture holes, a bracket with subclasses, e.g., with 90 or 100 degrees bending angle, or screws with subclasses such as metal screws or machine screws are examples for Class.

EXAMPLE 2   For facilitating an effective part retrieval for slotted screws, several Class objects may be defined to classify screws:

  • A Class *1 with description 'slotted screws' and three subclasses with the descriptions *2: 'slotted cheese head screws - product grade A', *3: 'slotted pan head screws - product grade A', and *4: 'slotted countersunk flat head screws - product grade A'.
  • Each of the Class objects is based on a Class that further defines where the definition of the Class comes from. For Class *1 this is a company internal ExternalClassSystem for 'screw classes'. For the other Class objects these are ISO standardized ExternalClassSystem objects, namely for *2 'ISO 1207', for *3 'ISO 1580', and for *4 'ISO 2010'.
  • The Class objects may be characterized further by ClassAttribute objects. According to ISO 1207, the Class *2 has the attributes *11 with id 'd' and description 'thread', *12 with id 'l' and description 'nominal length', *13 with id 'mechanical properties' and description 'property class', etc. The possible values 'M1.6', 'M2', ..., 'M10' for ClassAttribute *11 may be defined as PropertyValue objects in a set of the attribute allowedValues. The according specification is given as name of the AO PropertyValue. The PropertyValue refer as their definition to a PropertyDefinition with the propertyType 'nominal metric thread diameter'.
  • To identify the designation 'Cheese head screw ISO 1207 - M5 x 20 x 4.8', a subclass of Class *2 is defined with the same description and classification source and the description 'slotted cheese head screws ISO 1207 -M5 x 20 x 4.8' but with the values for Class_attribute corresponding to *11 restricted to 'M5' only, i.e., to get just the M5 screws, corresponding to *12 restricted to value '20' only, and corresponding to *13 restricted to value '4.8' only (for steel according to ISO 898-1 [7]).
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Class.id
Description:
the identifier or set of identifiers for the Class.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Class.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Class. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Class.versionId
Description:
the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the Class. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for fundamental concepts

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Class.definedIn

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassCategoryAssociation
Description:

A ClassCategoryAssociation is an association of a SpecificationCategory with a ProductClass. Additionally, this assignment specifies if the usage of one or more Specification objects belonging to this SpecificationCategory, is mandatory or optional for all products of that ProductClass.

NOTE 1   The assignment of a SpecificationCategory to a ProductClass does not replace the association of single members of the SpecificationCategory to the ProductClass.

NOTE 2   The following additional data can be assigned to a ClassCategoryAssociation: Approval, DateTimeString, and Effectivity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassCategoryAssociation.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ClassCategoryAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

the classifications of the ClassCategoryAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassCategoryAssociation.associatedCategory
Description:

the SpecificationCategory that is associated with the ProductClass.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassCategoryAssociation.associatedProductClass
Description:

the ProductClass for which the SpecificationCategory is valid.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassCategoryAssociation.mandatory
Description:

specifies whether the Specification objects referring to the associated SpecificationCategory have to be used or may be used (optional) for products within the referenced ProductClass. A value of 'true' indicates that the usage is mandatory.

EXAMPLE    The specification category 'radio' may be associated 'optional' to the product class of a car; the specification category 'engine' is an example for a 'mandatory' association.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassConditionAssociation
Description:

A ClassConditionAssociation is an association of a SpecificationExpression with a ProductClass. The meaning of this association is specified further by the attribute conditionType.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a ClassConditionAssociation: Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassConditionAssociation.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ClassConditionAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassConditionAssociation.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the ClassConditionAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassConditionAssociation.conditionType
Description:

specifies the meaning of the association. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'design case': The SpecificationExpression specifies a condition when a given object has to be designed and verified. This value of the conditionType is for information only and shall not be interpreted when querying design cases or usage cases. For such a query, the value of the attribute configurationType of Configuration shall be evaluated;

    NOTE 2   This value may be used to precise when a given BreakdownElement has to be studied by the design department so that it provides solutions appropriate for the case specified by the attributes associatedCondition and associatedProductClass.

  • 'identification': The SpecificationExpression specifies a condition that enables to distinguish the associated ProductClass from other ProductClass objects. This value is not applicable for a top level node in a hierarchy of ProductClass objects. This identification is part of the identification of all sub classes of this ProductClass;
  • 'part usage': The SpecificationExpression specifies a condition for the usage of the components of an AlternativeSolution, the usage of an PartOccurrence or for the application of a ProcessPlan or a ProcessOperationOccurrence in the products of the associatedProductClass. In this case, the ClassConditionAssociation shall be referenced by at least one Configuration object;
  • 'validity': The SpecificationExpression specifies a condition that is used to verify a ClassSpecificationAssociation for the associatedProductClass. That means that the SpecificationExpression evaluates to 'true' if the set of Specification objects is valid; otherwise it evaluates to 'false' with the meaning that the specified object is invalid for the ProductClass. The associatedCondition is valid for all products belonging to the associatedProductClass if conditionType is 'identification' or 'validity'.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassConditionAssociation.associatedCondition
Description:

specifies the SpecificationExpression that is assigned to the ProductClass.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassConditionAssociation.associatedProductClass
Description:

specifies the ProductClass for which the SpecificationExpression is valid.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassSpecificationAssociation
Description:

A ClassSpecificationAssociation is an association of a Specification with a ProductClass. The meaning of this association is specified further by the attribute associationType.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to a ClassSpecificationAssociation: Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassSpecificationAssociation.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ClassSpecificationAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassSpecificationAssociation.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the ClassSpecificationAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassSpecificationAssociation.associationType
Description:

the kind of availability of a particular Specification in a ProductClass. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'availability': The Specification is a potential characteristic of any product belonging to a high level ProductClass. It is not specified if this is an option or a standard;

    EXAMPLE 1   'front wheel drive' or 'four wheel drive' are available for a product class 'Voyager'.

  • 'identification': The Specification is a characteristic that enables to distinguish the associated ProductClass from other ProductClass objects. This is a kind of 'non replaceable standard'. This value is not applicable for a top level node in a hierarchy of ProductClass objects. This identification is part of the identification of all sub classes of this ProductClass;

    EXAMPLE 2   The car body type 'limousine' is identifying product class 'S40'.

  • 'non replaceable standard': The Specification is a characteristic of all products belonging to the ProductClass;

    EXAMPLE 3   'South East Asia climate zone' is a 'non replaceable standard' for a car that is produced for use in that particular geographic area.

  • 'option': The Specification is a characteristic of a product if explicitly chosen. The Specification replaces another Specification of the same SpecificationCategory if the replaced Specification is associated with the ProductClass as 'replaceable standard';

    EXAMPLE 4   'sun roof' or 'radio with CD' are common options proposed to the customer.

  • 'part usage': The Specification is a characteristic for the usage of the components of an AlternativeSolution, the usage of an PartOccurrence, or for the application of a ProcessPlan or a ProcessOperationOccurrence in the products of the associated ProductClass;
  • 'replaceable standard': The Specification is a default characteristic of the products belonging to the ProductClass as long as no other Specification of the same SpecificationCategory is chosen.

    EXAMPLE 5   'power brake' is a 'replaceable standard' for product class 'Golf'; it can be replaced by 'ABS', which is another specification of the same specification category 'brake system'.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassSpecificationAssociation.associatedProductClass
Description:

the ProductClass for which the Specification is valid.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ClassSpecificationAssociation.associatedSpecification
Description:

the Specification that is associated with the ProductClass.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssembly
Description:
A CompositeAssembly is a type of ConstituentPart that is made of multiple materials that are bonded together. A CompositeAssembly may be made from any combination of materials. A completed CompositeAssembly need not be a rigid shape. A CompositeAssembly may also be used as a composite part.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssembly.layupPart

identifies constituent parts that make up a CompositeAssembly.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssembly.shape

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssemblySequenceDefinition
Description:
A CompositeAssemblySequenceDefinition is a single unique sequence or layer within a CompositeAssembly. The sequence or layer contains one or more constituent parts. When more than one constituent part resides in the same sequence or layer, the constituents must not overlap.

NOTE 1   If constituents do overlap they must be put on separate sequence or layers.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssemblySequenceDefinition.componentsInSequence
Description:
specifies the collection of components in a single unique sequence or layer in a part. The componentsInSequence shall be a collection of one or more of the ComponentClassForAssemblySelect types.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssemblyTable
Description:
A CompositeAssemblyTable is a type of LaminateTable that provides an ordered list of constituent parts. The ordered list provides basic placement position within the laminate (see following figure).


Figure 4 —  Composite assembly table

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeAssemblyTable.sequenceGroups
Description:
specifies the groups of constituents to be laid in sequence. There shall exist not less than two CompositeAssemblySequenceDefinitions for the CompositeAssemblyTable.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeSheetRepresentation
Description:
A CompositeSheetRepresentation is a type of ConstituentShapeRepresentation that defines a sheet product. A sheet product is a product whose thickness is constant and small in comparison to its length and width. Most sheet products will conform to the surface on which they are placed. The shape of a sheet product can be represented in a 3-dimensional model of the actual shape, as a shape projected onto the layup surface, or as a shape projected into a 2-dimensional plane.

EXAMPLE    A typical composite sheet is 0.1 to 0.4 millimeters thick while its length and width are much greater than 25 millimeters.

A CompositeSheetRepresentation may be one of the following:
  • FaceBasedSheetRepresentation,
  • GeometricSheetRepresentation.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.CompositeSheetRepresentation.threeDGeometry
Description:
specifies the geometry of the CompositeSheetRepresentation.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration
Description:

A Configuration is a the association of a ClassConditionAssociation or a ClassSpecificationAssociation object with a design or with a process in order to define a valid usage of it in the context of a certain ProductClass.

NOTE 1   The validity of the association may be limited by a time period through assigning an Effectivity object to it.

NOTE 2   The semantics of the kind of association is defined by the attributes configurationType and inheritanceType.

NOTE 3   The following additional data can be assigned to a Configuration: Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the Configuration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the Configuration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration.configurationType
Description:

the valid usage of a Configuration object that is applied to the application object as configuredElement. The following values shall be used:

  • 'design': The object referenced as configuredElementhas to be designed and verified before it can actually be used in a given context. This context is specified by the ClassConditionAssociation and ClassSpecificationAssociation objects referenced as the isSolutionFor. This type of Configuration is applicable for AlternativeSolution, BreakdownElement, ProcessPlan, or ProcessOperationOccurrence objects;
  • 'usage': The object referenced as the configuredElement is controlled by a Configuration. The ClassConditionAssociation and ClassSpecificationAssociation objects specify the usage cases and are referenced as the isSolutionFor.

This type of Configuration is applicable for AlternativeSolution, PartOccurrence, ProcessPlan, ProcessOperationOccurrence, or PhysicalBreakdown objects.

EXAMPLE 1   The presence of an optional third rear axle of a truck is controlled by specifications on the level of PhysicalBreakdown.

EXAMPLE 2   A 'sunroof' has to be provided, i.e., designed for a class of vehicles that has an optional 'sunroof' as part of its specification.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration.inheritanceType
Description:

specifies whether or not an inheritance scheme for the configuration information in a hierarchical structure is applied to the application object referenced as the configuredElement. The levels within such a hierarchy are defined through RealizationOrOccurrenceRelationship objects or the attribute baseElement of AlternativeSolution. The following values shall be used:

  • 'exception': No inheritance scheme is applicable and all required configuration information must be attached locally at the application object. The value indicates that the configuration information may be inconsistent to the structural levels above it or that it is, on purpose, contradictory to it. Such a condition implies that an inheritance scheme shall not continue beyond this point in the product structure tree

EXAMPLE 3   A situation where the inheritanceType 'exception' is applicable is a technical solution released for one particular customer without support in higher structure levels.

  • 'inherited': A scheme for inheritance of configuration information applies. The complete configuration information shall be collected from the different levels in the structure by evaluation of results. The results shall be evaluated using the logical AND to combine configuration information starting at the referenced configuredElement and using the logical OR to combine alternatives. In addition, this evaluation shall consider related effectivity information. 'inherited' only applies for objects for which the same value of configurationType is defined;

EXAMPLE 4   The following figure shows how inheritance is applied along the tree of a product structure.




Figure 1 —   Inheritance along product structure tree

The complete configuration information of a PartOccurrence can be obtained by adding any such information to AlternativeSolution objects which are linked through RealizationOrOccurrenceRelationship objects and baseElement attributes respectively. Whenever more than one higher level instance is present, the current information available is branched in as many branches as instances are present. For example, the total configuration information for the PartOccurrence given in the figure above could be expressed as follows: (C0.0 AND C1.0 AND C2.0) OR (C0.0 AND C1.1 AND C2.1) OR (C0.0 AND C1.1 AND C2.2).

  • 'local': No inheritance scheme is applicable and all required configuration information must be attached locally at the application object. Nevertheless, any potentially inherited configuration information of a higher level shall be consistent, i.e., it shall be a subset of the locally defined configuration information.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration.configuredElement
Description:

the element that is controlled for its valid usage by the Configuration.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Configuration.isSolutionFor
Description:

the characteristic or combination of characteristics for which the object referenced as the configuredElement provides a solution or which is needed to control a process operation. These characteristics are defined by a ClassSpecificationAssociation and combinations of characteristics are defined by a ClassConditionAssociation where the attribute conditionType is 'part usage'.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ContentProperty
Description:
A ContentProperty is the specification of characteristics precising the content of a File or of a DocumentDefinition. Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ContentProperty.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ContentProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ContentProperty.detailLevel
Description:

the level of detail that the File or the DocumentDefinition provides. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'rough 3d shape': three-dimensional shape model without edge rounds and fillets;
  • 'rounded edges': three-dimensional shape model with edge rounds and fillets.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ContentProperty.geometryTypes
Description:

the kind or kinds of geometry that an object contains. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • '3D wireframe model': The document contains a three-dimensional shape model in wireframe representation;
  • '2D shape': The document contains a two-dimensional shape model or contours only;
  • 'surface model': The document contains a three-dimensional shape model in surface representation;
  • 'closed volume': The document contains a three-dimensional shape model in closed body topological surface representation;
  • 'solid model': The document contains a three-dimensional shape model in advanced boundary representation;
  • 'solid and surface model': The document contains a three-dimensional shape model in surface and advanced boundary representation;
  • 'assembly': The document contains an assembly structure with reference to the assembled components and their transformation matrices;
  • 'assembly with mating elements': The document contains an assembly structure including the mating components only, such as screws or rivets, with exact positioning information. This assembly representation is intended to be overlayed with the assembly structure for the main components;
  • '2D drawing': The document contains a technical drawing without three-dimensional shape representation;
  • 'drawing derived from 3D data': The document contains a technical drawing that has been derived from a three-dimensional shape model;
  • 'drawing related to 3D data': The document contains a technical drawing that visualizes a three-dimensional shape model and possibly establishes associative left to the three-dimensional shape model.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ContentProperty.languages
Description:

the language or languages which are used in the characterized objects.

EXAMPLE    'Japanese' and 'German' are examples for the fact that annotation on a drawing is provided in the language 'Japanese' or 'German' respectively.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

the scale that is used in the File or in the DocumentDefinition the ContentProperty is referred by. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DateAndPersonAssignment
Description:

A DateAndPersonAssignment is an object that associates a DateAndPersonOrganization with product data. This assignment provides additional information for the associated object. The provision of such data through this assignment has an organizational character whereas some objects require the same kind of data in order to be semantically complete. This assignment shall not be used to associate the corresponding organizational data with an object whose attributes are referencing the organizational data directly.

EXAMPLE 1   An example for the requirement stated is that there shall not exist a DateAndPersonAssignment with a role of 'requestor' that refers to a WorkRequest, since this object refers directly to DateAndPersonOrganization in that role.

NOTE    In the context of the object DateAndPersonAssignment, the expression 'referenced object' means 'a concept that is conveyed within one of the instances referred to by the attribute assignedTo and not one of the instances referred to by this attribute.

EXAMPLE 2   If applied to an instance of Part with role 'creation', the DateAndPersonAssignment specifies the creation date of the part, tool, or raw material as a new object in the activity domain of the organization, and not the creation date of the instance of Part in the product management system of the organization.

Description:

A DateTimeAssignment is an association of point in time specified as a DateTimeString with product data. This assignment provides additional information for the associated object. The provision of such data through this assignment has an organizational character whereas some objects require the same kind of data mandatorily in order to be semantically complete. This assignment shall not be used to associate the corresponding organizational data with an object whose attributes are referencing the organizational data directly.

EXAMPLE 1   An example for the requirement stated is that there shall not exist a DateTimeAssignment with a role of 'actual start date' that refers to an Activity, since this object refers directly to DateTimeString in that role.

NOTE    In the context of the object DateTimeAssignment, the expression 'referenced object' means a concept that is conveyed within one of the instances referred to by the attribute assignedTo and not one of the instances referred to by this attribute.

EXAMPLE 2   If applied to an instance of Part with role 'creation', the DateTimeAssignment specifies the creation date of the part, tool, or raw material as a new object in the activity domain, and not the creation date of the instance of Part in a product management system.

    EXAMPLE 5   This role is applicable, e.g., when referring to a PropertyDefinitionSelect.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the DocumentAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the DocumentAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the DocumentAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.role
Description:

the meaning of the assignment. Where applicable, the following values shall be used:

  • 'additional information': The assigned document provides information that is relevant for the associated object, but is not a description of the associated object itself;
  • 'behaviour': The assigned document specifies information about the behaviour of the associated object;
  • 'description': The assigned document provides textual information for the associated object itself;
  • 'informative': The assigned document may or may not be considered;
  • 'mandatory': The associated object shall conform to the content of the assigned document;
  • 'mathematical description': The assigned document specifies the associated object by providing the algorithmic specification of its behaviour.
  • 'dimensioning standard': The assigned document specifies the dimensioning standard;

    NOTE    The document shall be assigned to a PartView.

    EXAMPLE 2   For a BreakdownElement there is a textual document assigned, explaining the functionality, size, and other characteristics by a DocumentAssignment with role 'description'. Another document, representing the specification of the ProductClass, in which the BreakdownElement is used, is also assigned to the same BreakdownElement by a DocumentAssignment with role 'additional information'.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.assignedDocument
Description:
the assigned Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, or File.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.assignedTo
Description:

the objects to which the Document is assigned.

EXAMPLE 1   A document assigned to ActivityAssignment may provide further description of the input or output of that activity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentAssignment.documentPortion
Description:
the word or group of the words that convey the subject or sub contents of the document. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinition
Description:

A DocumentDefinition is one of potentially more alternative representations of a DocumentVersion.

NOTE 1   A DocumentVersion may have more than one representation.

EXAMPLE    A version of a logical document, which contains a shape model, may be represented in the different native formats of two three-dimensional CAD systems.

NOTE 2   The following additional data can be assigned to a DocumentDefinition: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship
Description:

A DocumentDefinitionRelationship is a relationship between two DocumentDefinition objects.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to a DocumentDefinitionRelationship: Approval, Effectivity, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the DocumentDefinitionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the DocumentDefinitionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'addition': The application object specifies that the related document provides supplementary or collateral information with regard to the information provided by the relating document;
  • 'copy': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition is a copy of the relating DocumentDefinition;
  • 'decomposition': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition is one of potentially more sub documents of the relating DocumentDefinition;

    EXAMPLE 1   The decomposition of a document into clauses is an example for the use of this value.

  • 'derivation': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition is derived from the relating DocumentDefinition;

    EXAMPLE 2   A raster image may be derived from a three-dimensional CAD model.

    EXAMPLE 3   A html version may be derived from a text document as an alternative.

  • 'peer': The application object specifies that the related document provides required information with regard to that provided by the relating document. The peer document is essential for a complete understanding;
  • 'reference': The application object defines a relationship where the related document is referenced from the relating;

    EXAMPLE 4   A hyperlink is an example for a 'reference'.

  • 'sequence': The application object defines a logical sequence where the related DocumentDefinition comes after the relating DocumentDefinition;

    EXAMPLE 5   A sequence of clauses.

  • 'substitution': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition replaces the relating DocumentDefinition;
  • 'translation': The DocumentDefinitionRelationship specifies that the related document is generated through a translation process from the relating document.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship.relating
Description:

one object of DocumentDefinition that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship.related
Description:

the other object of DocumentDefinition that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentDefinitionRelationship.wr:WR1
Description:
A DocumentDefinition shall not be related to itself.

Description:
A DocumentVersionRelationship is a is a relationship between two DocumentVersion objects.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentVersionRelationship.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the DocumentVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Description:
the classifications of the DocumentVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DocumentVersionRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'derivation': The business object defines a deriving relationship where the related DocumentVersion is based on the relating DocumentVersion which is an earlier version of the same or of a different Document;
  • 'hierarchy': The business object defines a hierarchical relationship where the related DocumentVersion is a sub version of the relating DocumentVersion;

    EXAMPLE    'Revision 1.1' and 'revision 1.2' are examples of sub-versions of 'version 1'.

  • 'sequence': The business object defines a version sequence where the relating DocumentVersion is the preceding version and the related DocumentVersion is the following version.
  • 'supplied document': The business object defines a relationship between two DocumentVersion objects representing the same object in different organizational contexts.

    NOTE 3   The different organizational contexts can be represented by different general organizational data associations with the related DocumentVersion objects.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.DrapedOrientationAngle
Description:
A DrapedOrientationAngle is a type of PlyOrientationAngle that defines a position and direction at a point within a part.

NOTE    The warp direction of a fabric shall be placed in the specified direction prior to draping over the part. Once the fabric has been draped, the orientation angle at any given point must be derived from the draped shape of the fabric. The DrapedOrientationAngle will change in the part if the surface of the part has complex curvature.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.EventRelationship
Description:

A EventRelationship is a relationship which exists between two Event objects.

EXAMPLE    An instance of this entity data type with relationType 'sequence' may be used to specify that an event shall end before another event starts.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.EventRelationship.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the EventRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.EventRelationship.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the EventRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.EventRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'actualization': The relationship specifies that the relating Event identifies a predicted or planned event and the related Event identifies the point in time when that event actually occurred. This relationship is valid if the actualStartDate attribute of the relating Event is not specified and the actualStartDate attribute of the related Event is specified, or, if both these attributes are specified and equal;
  • 'exclusiveness': The relationship specifies that the relating and the related Event shall not have any overlap during their duration;
  • 'sequence': The relationship specifies that the relating Event shall be completed before the related Event starts;
  • 'simultaneity': The relationship specifies that both the relating and related Event are considered as occurring during the same time period or shall be performed together in order to ensure consistency and enhance efficiency.

    NOTE    The criteria for 'simultaneity' and in particular the allowed delay between two events declared simultaneous, are user-dependent.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.EventRelationship.relating
Description:

one object of Event that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.EventRelationship.related
Description:

the other object of Event that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ExternalGeometricModel
Description:
An ExternalGeometricModel is a type of GeometricModel that contains geometry in a three-dimensional context only.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ExternalGeometricModel.accuracyType
Description:

the kind of accuracy that is applied. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'angular accuracy': A kind of accuracy that specifies the maximum value for the absolute angle between two curve tangents or two surface normals for which the creating system assumes curve tangents or surface normals being identical

    NOTE 1   The angular accuracy value can be used to determine the accuracy range for tangent continuous curve or surface connections.

  • 'curvature accuracy': A kind of accuracy that specifies the value for the term under which a system can assume that the two radii of curvature R1 and R2 are identical. The curvature accuracy value is used to determine the accuracy range for curvature continuous curve or surface connections

    NOTE 2   Terms surrounded by the FORMULA symbols represent the absolute values of these terms.

  • 'distance accuracy': A kind of accuracy that specifies the distance under which two points can be considered as having the same location. The distance accuracy value defined for a GeometricModel is valid for all geometric elements of the GeometricModel.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ExternalGeometricModel.accuracyValue
Description:
a numerical value defining the accuracy of the model. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

the DigitalFile that contains the externally defined geometry information.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.FormatProperty
Description:
A FormatProperty is a specification of characteristics of a File or of a DocumentDefinition that specify the format of the object. At least one of the optional attributes shall be specified for each instance of this object. In the case where a FormatProperty is referred by a DocumentDefinition the characteristics apply to all individual File objects, whereas in the case it is referred by a File the characteristics apply on an individual basis.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.FormatProperty.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the FormatProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.FormatProperty.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the FormatProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.FormatProperty.characterCode
Description:

the character code that is used in the characterized object. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'binary': The document contains data in binary format;
  • 'IEC 61286': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to IEC 61286;
  • 'ISO 646': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to ISO 646;

    NOTE 1   The character set in ISO 646 is identical to the character set commonly known as ASCII

  • 'ISO 6937': The coded character set used to encode the document data is according to ISO/IEC 6937;
  • 'ISO 8859-1': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to ISO 8859-1;

    NOTE 2   The character set in ISO 8859-1 is identical to the character set commonly known as LATIN-1.

  • 'ISO 10646': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to ISO/IEC 10646.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.FormatProperty.dataFormat
Description:

the convention that was used to structure the information in the characterized object. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'DXF': The document contains data in Drawing Exchange File format;
  • 'IGES': The document contains data in Initial Graphics Exchange Specification format;
  • 'ISO 10303-203': The document contains data in ISO 10303-203 format;
  • 'ISO 10303-214': The document contains data in ISO 10303-214 format;
  • 'TIFF CCITT GR4': The document contains data in TIFF CCITT GR4 format;
  • 'VDAFS': The document contains data in VDAFS format;
  • 'VOXEL': The document contains data in VOXEL format.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.FormatProperty.sizeFormat
Description:

the dimensions of a physical presentation of the object the sizeFormat is provided for.

EXAMPLE 1   'ISO A0' is an example for the sizeFormat of a drawing that is stored digitally.

EXAMPLE 2   '0.2 x 0.4 x 0.4 meters' is an example for the sizeFormat of a wooden model.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.GeneralShapeDependentProperty
Description:

A GeneralShapeDependentProperty is a type of ShapeDependentProperty that defines a user-defined characteristic of an object. The PropertyValue specified by a GeneralShapeDependentProperty is derived from geometry.

NOTE    The GeneralShapeDependentProperty may be used for the purpose of validation of geometric models.

EXAMPLE 1   If a geometry model is exchanged between two partners, the calculation of various properties of the bodies, such as centre of mass, overall surface, or overall volume, is performed by originator and recipient. When comparing these set of values, the existence of deficiencies in the received model can be easily detected.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.GeneralShapeDependentProperty.propertyType
Description:

the type of characteristic that is specified for an object. The following values shall be used:

  • 'centroid': The PropertyValue identifies the centre point of the mass of a body. The relative position of this point within the body is an invariant datum relative to rotation and translation.;

    EXAMPLE 2   An example, where the use of this GeneralShapeDependentProperty with propertyType 'centroid' is used instead of the object CentreOfMass, is the following: sometimes the GeneralShapeDependentProperty is calculated by some system at some point of time. But there are cases where the information, e.g., the GeneralShapeDependentProperty of a die, is transferred into a following stage, e.g., in order to perform a feasibility check, where there is only a simplified shape representation that does not allow to calculate the exact GeneralShapeDependentProperty. Yet, in this stage the information about the GeneralShapeDependentProperty is needed in order to check whether the transport of a die with a crane is feasible.

  • 'surface area': The PropertyValue specifies the overall surface of the bodies contained in the referenced shape.;
  • 'volume': The PropertyValue specifies the overall volume of the bodies contained in the referenced shape.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.GeneralShapeDependentProperty.propertyValue
Description:
the value that is given for a particular characteristic.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.GeneralShapeDependentProperty.unit
Description:
the unit in which the GeneralShapeDependentProperty is expressed. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight
Description:
A InformationRight is a definition of what may or may not be done with an item of information in the sense of legal rights and obligations.

EXAMPLE 1   Copyright is an InformationRight.

EXAMPLE 2   For the purposes of developing a new system, details of government furnished equipment may be made available to a particular project team. The team may copy and use the information internally, but may not pass it on, either to a third part, or to another team, and must destroy the information at the end of the contract.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the InformationRight.

NOTE 1   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the InformationRight is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the InformationRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the InformationRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight.owners
Description:

the set of Organization or PersonInOrganization objects that own the InformationRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationRight.restriction
Description:

the text that describes any conditions and limitations that apply to the exercise of the right. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

EXAMPLE 3   The description of the right states that copying is permitted within the project team only, whereas the restriction notes the additional constraint that the information must be destroyed at the end of the project.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight
Description:
An InformationUsageRight is an application an InformationRight to a particular usage context.

NOTE 1   One view of the distinction between an InformationRight and an InformationUsageRight is that the InformationRight represents a standard clause in a contract, whereas an InformationUsageRight represents the fact that the clause is used in a particular contract.

NOTE 2   The context for the usage can be defined through the contract which defines the right, the organization that grants the right, the person or organization which is granted the right, and any dates such as the starting or ending dates for the right. The meaning of each association is identified through the roles of the assignments, and these are defined through reference data.

NOTE 3   The Approval of an InformationUsageRight carries the meaning that the right is granted to all information items in the relevant context, as opposed to the approval of an InformationUsageRightAssignment which is limited to particular items.

NOTE 4   InformationUsageRight provides a mechanism for recording significant rights within a product database. The legal significance of the presence or absence of a right is outside the scope of this part of ISO 10303.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the InformationUsageRight.

NOTE 5   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the InformationUsageRight is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the InformationUsageRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the InformationUsageRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight.grantsRight
Description:

the set of InformationRight granted under this usage.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRight.owners
Description:

the set of Organization or PersonInOrganization objects that own the InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRightAssignment
Description:
A InformationUsageRightAssignment is an assignment of a particular usage right to a set of items.

NOTE 1   If an Approval is applied to this entity, it carries the meaning that the particular set of items is approved for the given usage. This approval generally indicates that the approval is exceptional, for example, where the information belongs to another project, and that project agrees to share some particular items of information. There is a further implication that the set of entities should not be changed once the approval is given.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRightAssignment.id

the identifier or set of identifiers for the InformationUsageRightAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Description:
the classifications of the InformationUsageRightAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRightAssignment.role
Description:

the meaning of the assignment/association. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRightAssignment.assignedRight
Description:

the InformationUsageRight which is assigned to the items.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.InformationUsageRightAssignment.isAssignedTo
Description:

the set of InformationUsageRightAssignmentSelect to which the InformationUsageRight applies.

EXAMPLE 1   Where one InformationUsageRight supersedes another, then the original right is pointed to by the relating attribute, its replacement by the related attribute, and the relationType attribute takes the value supersedes.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MakeFromRelationship
Description:

A MakeFromRelationship is a type of PartViewRelationship that is a relationship between a PartView which provides the definition of a raw material, or of a semi-finished part and a PartView which provides the definition of an object manufactured out of that material, or semi-finished part. The inherited attribute related specifies the raw material or the semi-finished part, and the inherited attribute relating specifies the manufactured part.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MakeFromRelationship.priority
Description:

an integer that ranks the preference for use of the related PartVersion among all instances of MakeFromRelationship that have the same value for the inherited relating attribute. This value is an integer that only has meaning when comparing it with corresponding values for MakeFromRelationship sharing the same relating PartView object. It is a relative ranking value, not an absolute ranking. A lower value indicates a higher preference for the related PartView object, and a higher value indicates a lower preference. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MakeFromRelationship.quantity
Description:

the ValueWithUnit that specifies the amount of the related PartVersion that is used to produce the relating PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified; it may be specified when the related PartVersion is a countable material.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MakeFromRelationship.relationType

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'value': value description;

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MatingDefinition
Description:

A MatingDefinition is a type of AssemblyDefinition. It is a view of a PartVersion, defining the physical connection of two or more PartOccurrence objects. It includes technical information about the kind of connection. This information is independent from the hierarchical assembly structure.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MatingDefinition.matingType
Description:

the kind of mating, that is, how the items shall be mated together. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'bolted joint': Attachment of two or more items that are screwed together using screws, bolt nuts, and washers;
  • 'brazing': Attachment of two or more items established by soldering or brazing;
  • 'clasping': Attachment of two or more items established by using a clamp at one common outer border;
  • 'clinching': Attachment of two or more items established by pressing these items together and stamping texture at the point of contact;
  • 'clipping': Attachment of two or more items established by a clip ( e.g. fixing the inner door panel at the inner door plate);
  • 'doweling': Attachment of two or more items using a pin that is fit into each of each part by pressing;
  • 'flanging': Attachment of two or more items by crimping a projected length of one part over the edge of the other part;
  • 'foam injection': Attachment of two or more items where foam is injected into a cavity to establish the connection;
  • 'gluing': Attachment of two items established by adhesion material;
  • 'laser-welding': Attachment of two or more items that are welded together using a laser technique;
  • 'press fit': Attachment of two or more items obtained by forces resulting from the selected size tolerances;
  • 'riveting': Attachment of two or more items that are riveted together at a certain spot using a rivet;
  • 'sewing': Attachment of two or more items that are sewn together;

    EXAMPLE    Upholstering cloth is sewn together to form a seat pillow.

  • 'spot welding': Attachment of two or more items that are welded together at a certain welding spot;
  • 'stapling': Attachment of two or more items at a certain spot using a nail or a wire stitch to establish the connection;
  • 'welding': Attachment of two or more items by welding together with one weld bead.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.MatingDefinition.matedParts
Description:

the set of two or more MatedPartAssociation that reference a MatingDefinition instance as values of their attributes with name relating.
