Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment
Description:
An OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment is an object that associates an Organization or a PersonInOrganization with product data. This assignment provides additional information for the associated object. The provision of such data through this assignment has an organizational character whereas some objects require the same kind of data in order to be semantically complete. This assignment shall not be used to associate the corresponding organizational data with an object whose attributes are referencing the organizational data directly. The OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment shall not be used for the purpose of specifying a relationship between two PersonInOrganization objects, e.g., a succession in organizational responsibility. For these purposes, PersonInOrganizationRelationship shall be used.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment.role
Description:

specifies the responsibility of the assigned Person or Organization with respect to the object that it is applied to. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'author': The referenced object has been created by the assigned Person or Organization. The author holds the copyright;
  • 'classification officer': The assigned Person or Organization is formally responsible for the classification of the referenced object;
  • 'creator': The referenced object has been created by the assigned Person or Organization;
  • 'custodian': The assigned Person or Organization is responsible for the existence and integrity of the referenced object;
  • 'customer': The assigned Person or Organization acts as a purchaser or consumer of the referenced object;
  • 'design supplier': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who delivers the data describing the referenced object;

    EXAMPLE    The 'design supplier' may be a design by means of a three-dimensional model or a drawing.

  • 'editor': One or more attributes have been modified by the assigned Person or Organization;
  • 'id owner': The assigned Person or Organization is the one responsible for the designation of an identifier;
  • 'location': The assigned Organization is the place where the referenced object can be found or where it takes place;
  • 'manufacturer': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who produces the actual (physical) object;
  • 'owner': The assigned Person or Organization owns the referenced object, and has final say over its disposition and any changes to it;
  • 'read access’: The assigned Person or Organization neither has the right to modify any attributes of the referenced object, nor to modify, create or delete objects that are attached directly or indirectly to the referenced object;
  • 'supplier': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who delivers the actual (physical) object (e.g., a dealer);
  • 'wholesaler': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who is in the sales chain between the manufacturer and the supplier;
  • 'write access': The assigned Person or Organization has the right to modify the attributes of the referenced object, as well as to modify, create, or delete objects that are attached directly or indirectly to the referenced object.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment.assignedPersonOrOrganization

specifies the concerned Organization or the PersonInOrganization.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Part
Description:

A Part is a identification of definition of a part. It collects the definitional information of the versions of a part. A Part shall always be categorized as 'piece part', 'product', 'software', 'tool', or 'raw material' using a ClassSelect.

NOTE 1   A Part does not represent an actual physical object of the real world.

NOTE 2   A Part may be either a single piece part, an assembly of arbitrary complexity, a raw material, or a tool.

EXAMPLE 1   In the context of cars, a Part may be the car as a whole, the assembly of the engine, the car body, a fender, the side window glass, grease, or a stamping die.

EXAMPLE 2   In the context of aeroplanes, a Part may be the air plane as a whole, the assembly of the engine, the body of the air plane, a fender, the side window glass, grease, or a stamping die.

NOTE 3   A Part is identified by an organization. The definition of the domain of uniqueness and the mechanism for guaranteeing the uniqueness of Part id are outside the scope of this capability.

NOTE 4   A Part may have zero or more versions. Versions of a Part are represented by the entity PartVersion.

NOTE 5   The following additional data can be assigned to a Part: ActivityMethod, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Part.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the Part.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Part.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the Part is known.

NOTE 7   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Part.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Part. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Part.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the Part. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Part.partTypes
Description:

specifies the ClassSelect objects of the Part.

NOTE 8   The partTypes is used to distinguish a part in the Bill of Material (BOM).

NOTE 9   For the attribute id a set of predefined values is specified hereafter. If values other than the proposed ones are used, they should be of general categorizing nature. This kind of categorization ought not to be used to classify names or identifiers of objects, e.g., in order to classify part families; for this purposes ought to be used.

NOTE 10   A Part shall always be categorized as 'piece part', 'product', 'software', 'tool', or 'raw material'.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartOccurrence
Description:

A PartOccurrence is an occurrence of an object in a product structure that is defined either by a PartVersion, PartView or as a ProductConfiguration.

EXAMPLE    In the case of a car, the Item 'wheel' is defined once. Its PartVersion carries all the information necessary to define the wheel (e.g., its shape) independent of its usage. Additionally, there are 5 PartOccurrence objects for this wheel since there are 5 equal wheels used in a car: Front-left, front-right, rear-left, rear-right, and spare wheel. Each of these instances may carry additional information such as placement or function. Each PartOccurrence is a SinglePartOccurrence, a QuantifiedPartOccurrence, a SelectedPartOccurrence, or a SpecifiedPartOccurrence.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartOccurrence: Approval, BreakdownVersion, Certification, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PartOccurrence, PartVersion, BreakdownElement, IndividualPartView, RequirementView, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

the classifications of the PartOccurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartOccurrence.definition
Description:

the PartVersion, PartView or the ProductConfiguration that serves as a definition for this particular occurrence. If an appropriate PartVersion or PartView is available, this object shall be used as definition, otherwise a ProductConfiguration shall be referenced.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersion
Description:

A PartVersion is an identification of a version of a part. It serves as the collector of the data characterizing a realizable object in various application contexts.

NOTE 1   A PartVersion is a part that may be produced, consumed, used to produce other PartVersion objects, or offered to the market.

NOTE 2   The collection of defining information may be incomplete, i.e., not all of the PartView objects needed to define a PartVersion are associated with the PartVersion.

NOTE 3   The set of all PartVersion objects of a Part represents the history of the Part within a particular life cycle stage or over its complete life cycle.

NOTE 4   A PartVersion does not have to be referenced by any PartView.

NOTE 5   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartVersion: ActivityMethod, Approval, Certification, Contract, DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PartOccurrence, BreakdownElement, IndividualPartView, RequirementView, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersion.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the PartVersion.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersion.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersion.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersion.sameAs
Description:
the proxies of the PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersion.views
Description:
the set of PartView objects that are defined for the PartVersion.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship
Description:

A PartVersionRelationship is a relationship between two instances of PartVersion. Unless specified in a specialization of this object, this relationship does not involve inheritance of data between the two related objects.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartVersionRelationship: Approval, Certification, DateTimeString, and InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PartVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the PartVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'derivation': The application object defines a deriving relationship where the related PartVersion is based on the relating PartVersion which is an earlier version of the same or of a different Part;
  • 'hierarchy': The application object defines a hierarchical relationship where the related PartVersion is a subordinate version of the relating PartVersion;

    EXAMPLE 1   'Rev. 1.1' and 'rev. 1.2' are subordinates of 'version 1'.

  • 'sequence': The application object defines a version sequence where the relating PartVersion is the preceding version of the related PartVersion that is the following version. For a given PartVersion there shall be at most one PartVersionRelationship of this relationType referring to this PartVersion as ' relating' and at most one PartVersionRelationship of this relationType referring as related.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship.relating
Description:

one object of PartVersion that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship.related
Description:

the other object of PartVersion that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.PartVersionRelationship.wr:WR1
Description:

the related object and the relating object must not be the same PartVersion

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationDefinition
Description:

A ProcessOperationDefinition is a specification of an activity that may be included in a ProcessPlan. A ProcessOperationDefinition characterizes a manufacturing or control operation.

NOTE 1   ProcessOperationDefinition as well as ProcessOperationOccurrence may be associated with organizational data using, e.g., OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The reason for having these data available for both types of objects is the requirement to associate ProcessOperationDefinition with organizational data in both a context independent and a context dependent way (the context is a particular ProcessPlan).

NOTE 2   In the case where an instance of ProcessOperationDefinition is associated with, e.g., two Organization objects (e.g., as location), once context independent and once context dependent, the two locations need not be the same, but should be related in a way that the context dependent location should be a specialization of the context independent location e.g., a particular assembly line in a plant).

NOTE 3   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProcessOperationDefinition: DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationDefinition.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProcessOperationDefinition.

Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'alternative': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationDefinition may be used alternatively instead of the relating ProcessOperationDefinition;
  • 'substitution': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationDefinition replaces the relating ProcessOperationDefinition;
  • 'version association': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationDefinition is a version of the relating ProcessOperationDefinition. In this case, only the related ProcessOperationDefinition shall specify a versionId;
  • 'version sequence': the application object defines a relationship where the relating ProcessOperationDefinition is the preceding version and the related ProcessOperationDefinition is the following version. In this case, both ProcessOperationDefinition objects shall specify a versionId.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship
Description:

A ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship is a relationship between two ProcessOperationOccurrence objects.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'decomposition': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationOccurrence is one of the components of the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  • 'exclusiveness': the application object defines a relationship where the relating and the related ProcessOperationOccurrence shall not have any overlap in time of execution;
  • 'sequence': the application object defines a relationship where the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence shall be completed before the related ProcessOperationOccurrence starts;
  • 'simultaneity': the application object defines a relationship where the relating and the related ProcessOperationOccurrence objects are considered as occurring during the same time period;

NOTE 1   The criteria for 'simultaneity' and in particular the allowed delay between two ProcessOperationOccurrence objects declared simultaneous, are user-dependent.

NOTE 2   See attribute cycleTime for additional information.

  • 'substitution': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationOccurrence replaces of the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship.relating
Description:

one object of ProcessOperationOccurrence that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

the other object of ProcessOperationOccurrence that is part of the relationship.

the interval of time within which both ProcessOperationOccurrence objects have to take place in order to be declared as simultaneous. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship.waitingTime
Description:

the time which shall elapse, at least, between the completion of the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence and the start of the related ProcessOperationOccurrence. The referenced shall have a definition that is a Duration.

EXAMPLE    The ProcessOperationOccurrence 'polishing' must not be started less than 2 hours after the ProcessOperationOccurrence 'painting' ended.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProcessOperationResourceAssignment.referenceTool
Description:

specifies whether or not the resource identified by the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment plays the role of the reference tool for the occurrence of an operation. In the case where the value of this attribute is 'true', all geometric transformations within the scope of the ProcessOperationOccurrence are defined with respect to the local coordinate system of the resource identified by the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment. There shall not be more than one resource playing the role of the reference tool for one ProcessOperationOccurrence. In the case where the resource is not represented as a PartView, the value of the attribute referenceTool shall be 'false'.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductClass
Description:

A ProductClass is an identification of a set of similar products to be offered to the market. ProductClass objects that are related to each other by a ProductClassRelationship do not inherit any characteristics from each other.

EXAMPLE    The following figure depicts a detail of an example of a structure that is built up by ProductClass and ProductClassRelationship objects.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProductClass: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

Description:

the classifications of the ProductClass. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductClass.levelType
Description:

the level of the ProductClass in a hierarchical structure of ProductClass objects.

EXAMPLE    A high level ProductClass (levelType = 'enterprise') may be used to define all SpecificationCategory and Specification objects for all ProductClass objects of an enterprise with several brands and companies. A second level ProductClass (levelType = 'platform') may be used to group all products that are based on the same technical concept (platform); these products may belong to different brands. A third level ProductClass (levelType = 'car family') may be used to group all products that have a common base and a fixed set of characteristics (specification categories). A fourth level ProductClass (levelType = 'car type') may represent products that are offered to the market; this level of ProductClass may be defined by the marketing department. A set of specifications sufficient to produce the car is associated with its ProductClass. Within this association, a distinction is made between standard characteristics (e.g. number of doors) and options that have to be chosen (e.g., outside colour) or that may be chosen by the customer (e.g., radio).

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductClass.marketSegmentType
Description:

the text that identifies a marketing category of the ProductClass. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration
Description:

A ProductConfiguration is a manufacturable object, or expected as so. A ProductConfiguration is defined with respect to the ProductClass it is a member of.

NOTE 1   The kind of product that is to be manufactured from the data of the ProductConfiguration, is the kind of product that the memberOf identifies a class of.

NOTE 2   The intent of ProductConfiguration is the identification of one manufacturable object whereas the intent of ProductClass is the gathering of products with similar characteristics.

EXAMPLE 1   A ProductConfiguration that is associated with a ProductClass that identifies a family of diesel engines is intended to lead to the manufacture of a particular case of diesel engine, and the ProductConfiguration that is associated with a ProductClass that identifies a car family will lead to the manufacture of a car.

NOTE 3   The entity ProductConfiguration corresponds to the concept of configuration item defined, in some configuration management standards, as an item subject to configuration management.

EXAMPLE 2   A ProductConfiguration may represent a component of a contracted product, onto which severe safety rules apply and for which configuration management is therefore rigorously applied.

NOTE 4   A ProductConfiguration may identify a variation of a ProductClass, an entire ProductClass, or some portion thereof.

NOTE 5   A ProductConfiguration can be established prior to the existence of a corresponding product.

For a ProductConfiguration one or more additional Specification objects may be specified. In this case they enhance the characterization provided for the associated ProductClass.

NOTE 6   The actual set of Specification objects for a ProductConfiguration are obtained by the union of definingSpecifications and of the Specification objects related to the associatedProductClass through a ClassSpecificationAssociation or a ClassConditionAssociation with associationType 'identification' or 'non replaceable standard'.

NOTE 7   The specification of a ProductConfiguration may be incomplete: there may not be in definingSpecifications any instance of Specification for some SpecificationCategory declared as mandatory for the associatedProductClass. For these SpecificationCategory objects any Specification available in the context of the associatedProductClass is considered as valid for the manufacturing of the product characterized by the considered ClassSpecificationAssociation.

EXAMPLE 3   If the colour is not specified for a given car family, the vehicle resulting from the realization of a ProductConfiguration associated to the ProductClass representing the car family may be without paint or painted in any available colour.

NOTE 8   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProductConfiguration: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, Contract, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProductConfiguration.

NOTE 9   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the ProductConfiguration is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 10   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProductConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.versionId
Description:

the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the ProductConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 11   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the ProductConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.definingSpecifications
Description:

the set of Specification objects necessary to discriminate the ClassSpecificationAssociation within its ProductClass. Each definingSpecifications shall be associated with a ProductClass by a ClassSpecificationAssociation with associationType not equal 'part usage'. The associated ProductClass shall be either the associated ProductClass of the ProductConfiguration or any higher level ProductClass related directly or indirectly by a ProductClassRelationship with a relationType 'hierarchy'. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductConfiguration.memberOf
Description:

the ProductClass that a ProductConfiguration belongs to.

the ProductPartEquivalence that associates this ProductConfiguration with a PartVersion.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ProductPartEquivalence

A ProductPartEquivalence is a mechanism to associate an PartVersion with its corresponding ProductConfiguration. It specifies the explicit design that corresponds to the ProductConfiguration. The ProductPartEquivalence represents the statement that, in all definition contexts, the PartVersion is a valid way to implement the ProductConfiguration.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.QuantifiedPartOccurrence
Description:

A QuantifiedPartOccurrence is the identification of the quantified occurrence of an object that is defined either as a PartOccurrence, PartView or as a ProductConfiguration.

EXAMPLE 1   Radiator liquid or engine oil are examples for QuantifiedPartOccurrence objects.

EXAMPLE 2   In a TechnicalSolution for the front left brake a certain screw is used four times.

A QuantifiedPartOccurrence is a type of PartOccurrence.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.QuantifiedPartOccurrence.quantity
Description:

a NumericalValue specifying the quantity of occurrences. If the quantity can not be expressed as a particular value, the concept of SelectedPartOccurrence shall be used instead to represent this instance.

NOTE    The quantity may be specified as a count measure, as a mass measure, as a length measure, as an area measure, or as a volume measure.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ReplacedUsageRelationship.usageContext
Description:

the object that identifies the context in which the replacement is applicable. In the case where usage_context refers to a RealizationOrOccurrenceRelationship, the relating PartOccurrence object of the ReplacedUsageRelationship shall be referred to as related by the RealizationOrOccurrenceRelationship.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement
Description:
A Requirement is an essential characteristic, condition, or capability that shall be met or exceeded by a system or a component to satisfy a contract, standard, specification, or other formally imposed document.

NOTE 1   The term "requirement" is used here in the sense that term is used in systems engineering and similar industrial domains.

NOTE 2   There may be many versions of a Requirement through RequirementVersion. There may also be more than one domain-specific view of a given RequirementVersion (using the RequirementView entity). The Requirement entity is simply a placeholder for holding a unique requirement. Most associations and properties could be defined at the Requirement, RequirementVersion or RequirementView level - that is in the context of a domain.

EXAMPLE    A requirement may be identified as "NOx emissions requirement", and uniquely identified as "Req2".

NOTE 3   Systems engineering tools and organizations may use differing identification mechanisms. Multiple identifiers may be managed in Requirement using the id attribute.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the Requirement.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the Requirement is known.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement.classifiedAs
Description:
the classifications of the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement.sameAs
Description:
the proxies of the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Requirement.versions
Description:
the versions of the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementAssignment
Description:
A RequirementAssignment is used to relate a Requirement (via RequirementVersion or RequirementView) to data types representing the items (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) which are affected by the requirement.

EXAMPLE    A requirement "the vehicle shall have a maximum power output of at least 150BHP" could be assigned to the data types which are used to represent the vehicle's engine.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementAssignment.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementAssignment.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementAssignment.description

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Description:
the classifications of the RequirementAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementAssignment.assignedRequirement
Description:
the RequirementVersion or the RequirementView which is assigned.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementAssignment.assignedTo
Description:
the item (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) which has the requirement assigned to it.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementCollectionRelationship
Description:
A RequirementCollectionRelationship is a type of RequirementViewRelationship. It identifies a collection relationship that is used to relate a parent (collection) requirement to its member requirements. This provides a method for collecting together a set of requirements and treating them as a single requirement, whilst still being able to refer to individual requirements.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementCollectionRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class name shall be used:

  • 'collection': the relationType specifies that the RequirementViewRelationship is a collection;
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementDecompositionRelationship
Description:
A RequirementDecompositionRelationship is a type of RequirementCollectionRelationship. It identifies a decomposition relationship. This provides a method to represent a decomposition of requirements.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementDecompositionRelationship.relationType
Description:

the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class name shall be used:

  • 'decomposition': the relationType specifies that the RequirementViewRelationship is a decomposition;
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSatisfactionAssertion
Description:
A RequirementSatisfactionAssertion is a relationship between an item (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) and a requirement (via RequirementVersion or the RequirementView), asserting that the item satisfies the identified requirement.

EXAMPLE    A data type used to represent a vehicle's engine with a power output of 160BHP could be asserted to satisfy a requirement "the vehicle shall have a maximum power output of at least 150BHP".

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Description:
the classifications of the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.assertedBy
Description:
the date and the Organization or the PersonInOrganization (via DateAndPersonOrganization) that has asserted the requirement satisfaction. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.relatedAssignment
Description:
the RequirementAssignment that is satisfied by the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.satisfiedBy
Description:
the item (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) that satisfies the requirement.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.satisfiedRequirement

  • 'sequence': the relationType specifies that the RequirementVersionRelationship is a sequence;
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSourceAssociation
Description:
A RequirementSourceAssociation is a relationship between a requirement (via the RequirementVersion or the RequirementView) and the data types representing the source (specified in RequirementSourceSelect) of the requirement.

EXAMPLE    The source of the requirement "the vehicle shall have a maximum power output of at least 150BHP" could be a document representing the findings of a market survey of sports car buyers.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementSourceAssociation.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementSourceAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementTracingRelationship
Description:
A RequirementTracingRelationship is a type of RequirementViewRelationship. It identifies a tracing relationship.

EXAMPLE    A requirement on the performance of a catalytic converter in a car may be traced from a more general emissions requirement.

A requirement may trace to many other requirements and vice versa - this is achieved by creating multiple instances of the tracing relationship entity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementVersion

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementView
Description:
A RequirementView provides a view of a requirement version relevant for one or more application domains. This view collects requirement data for specific engineering purposes.

EXAMPLE    An engineer may have responsibility for collecting all requirements associated with the cooling of an engine - covering engine block, tubing, water pump, electric fan.

Some requirements in a RequirementView might impact on different disciplines. Multiple RequirementView instances may be used to present different views of a given requirement for each discipline.

The definition of the requirement is represented by a set of definitional properties referenced from RequirementView.definitionalRepresentations. If more than one definitional property is provided each property shall be equivalent. Any other property that is associated with the RequirementView is assumed to be a non-defining property, such as an annotation etc.

EXAMPLE    The requirement that the weight should be less than 4 Kgs can be represented by a string representation "weight must be 4Kg" and a numeric representation "4Kg" specified as a value with units.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementView.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Description:
the set of ViewContext objects in which this view of the RequirementVersion is also relevant. The additionalContexts shall not contain the ViewContext that is referenced as the initialContext. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

the properties that define the requirement.

the ViewContext in which this view of the RequirementVersion has been designed primarily.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SelectedPartOccurrence
Description:

A SelectedPartOccurrence is a type of PartOccurrence that is the identification of the occurrence of an object that is either defined as a PartVersion, PartView or as a ProductConfiguration and whose quantity depends on certain constraints.

EXAMPLE 1   In a BOM where the exact amount of grease or glue can usually not be specified as a quantity, the specification of this grease or glue are examples for SelectedPartOccurrence objects.

EXAMPLE 2   To minimize the concentricity error of a wheel, weights are attached to the rim; this set of weights is a SelectedPartOccurrence. The quantity as well as the position of these weights depends on the concentricity behaviour of each particular wheel as manufactured and tested.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SelectedPartOccurrence.criterion
Description:

the constraint that has to be evaluated for the SelectedPartOccurrence.

EXAMPLE 3   'as required for balance' and 'as required for lubrication' are examples for a criterion.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SelectedPartOccurrence.quantity
Description:

the quantity of the part, tool or raw material foreseen as SelectedPartOccurrence. The quantity shall be of type ValueLimit or ValueRange.

NOTE    If the quantity is to be specified as a minimum and/or a maximum, then ValueLimit or ValueRange may be used.

EXAMPLE 4   The quantity of engine oil used in a car may be in the range of 3.7 to 3.9 litres. This is expressed using ValueRange as the quantity.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SerialConfiguration
Description:

A SerialConfiguration is a type of ManufacturingConfiguration that applies onwards from a given serial number of the product that is considered within the object referred to as isSolutionFor.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SerialConfiguration.endNumber
Description:

the serial number of that instance of the product that is the last instance for which the SerialConfiguration applies. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    If the endNumber is not specified, it is not foreseen that the SerialConfiguration ceases to be valid; i.e., the SerialConfiguration is expected to apply to all serial numbers greater than the serial start number for the product for whose characteristics the SerialConfiguration identifies a solution.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SerialConfiguration.startNumber
Description:

the serial number of that instance of the product that is the first instance for which the SerialConfiguration applies.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SizeProperty
Description:
A SizeProperty is the specification of the size of a File or of a DocumentDefinition object. At least one of the optional attributes shall be specified for each instance of this object. In the case where a SizeProperty is referred by a DocumentDefinition, the size information is the sum of the sizes of all individual objects that are collected by this object, whereas in the case it is referred by a File, the size information is the one of the individual objects that is referenced.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SizeProperty.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SizeProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SizeProperty.fileSize
Description:

the ValueWithUnit that represents the size of a digitally stored document. The value of this attribute need not be specified. The fileSize shall only be applied in cases where the SizeProperty is referred by a DigitalDocumentDefinition or a File.

EXAMPLE 1   '15021 Bytes' and 'less than 500 Bytes' are examples for a fileSize.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SizeProperty.pageCount
Description:

the number of pages of the application object the SizeProperty is referred by. The value of this attribute need not be specified. The pageCount shall only be used in cases where the SizeProperty is referred by a Hardcopy or a PhysicalDocumentDefinition.

EXAMPLE 2   '42 pages' and 'more than 1 page' are examples of a pageCount.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification
Description:

A Specification is a characteristic of a product. A Specification discriminates one product from other members of the same ProductClass. A Specification refers to a SpecificationCategory that completes the semantics of the Specification.

NOTE 1   A Specification may be a characteristic of the members of more than one ProductClass using BreakdownAssignment objects.

NOTE 2   A Specification in combination with a Configuration may be used to define under which conditions a Part is used in combination with a ProductClass.

EXAMPLE    'coupe', 'hatch back', or 'sedan' are examples for specifications belonging to the SpecificationCategory of type 'car body'. 'radio 1 with CD player' and 'radio 2 without CD player' are examples for specifications belonging to the SpecificationCategory of type 'radio equipment'. 'disk brake' and 'drum brake' are examples for specifications belonging to the SpecificationCategory of type 'braking system'.

NOTE 3   The following additional data can be assigned to a Specification: Approval, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the Specification.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.name
Description:

the words or set of words by which the Specification is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 5   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Specification. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.versionId
Description:

the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the Specification. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the Specification. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.category
Description:

the SpecificationCategory that completes the semantics of the Specification.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.Specification.package
Description:

specifies whether this Specification represents a package of Specification objects or not. Such a Specification combines those Specification objects that shall be offered to the market as a set. In the case where package is 'true', there shall be exactly one SpecificationInclusion per ProductClass considered, that refers to this Specification by its attribute ifCondition. The Specification objects that are members of the package, shall be specified in the attribute includedSpecification of the SpecificationInclusion.

NOTE 7   Commercial packages may be defined by the marketing department.

NOTE 8   Usually the members of a package belong to distinct SpecificationCategory objects.

EXAMPLE    A sports package contains sports seats, a special steering wheel, special tyres and wheels. A winter package contains heated front seats, heated windshield washers, heated exterior mirrors, and special tyres.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationCategory
Description:

A SpecificationCategory is a definition of a set of Specification objects serving the same purpose.

EXAMPLE 1   The category 'kind of drive' for the Specification objects 'front wheel drive' and 'rear wheel drive' or the category 'level of equipment' for the Specification objects 'standard', 'comfortable', and 'luxurious' are examples for SpecificationCategory objects.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a SpecificationCategory: Approval, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationCategory.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the SpecificationCategory.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationCategory.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SpecificationCategory.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationCategory.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the SpecificationCategory. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationCategory.implicitExclusiveCondition
Description:

specifies whether the Specification objects within the SpecificationCategory are mutually exclusive for the production of one particular product. A value of 'true' indicates that the referenced objects are mutually exclusive for the production of the particular product.

EXAMPLE 2   'safety equipment' is an example for a non mutually exclusive SpecificationCategory if, e.g., ABS and air bag are Specification objects in this category. 'engine' is an example for a SpecificationCategory with an implicitExclusiveCondition since usually only one engine can be mounted for power supply.

NOTE 3   More complex conditions can be handled using SpecificationExpression objects.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationCategoryHierarchy

Description:

the classifications of the SpecificationExpression. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationExpression.operands
Description:

the operands of the Boolean operation that are either Specification objects or other SpecificationExpression objects. In case theOperation is 'not' there shall be exactly one operand.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationExpression.theOperation
Description:

the kind of Boolean operation. The following kinds of operations are permitted:

  • 'and': all of the identified Specification objects shall be used;
  • 'or': a subset or all of the identified Specification objects shall be used;
  • 'oneof': exactly one of the identified Specification objects shall be used;
  • not': The identified Specification shall not be used. 'not' is an unary operation.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationInclusion
Description:

A SpecificationInclusion is a representation of the statement that specifies that the application of a Specification or of a SpecificationExpression implies the inclusion of an additional Specification or SpecificationExpression.

EXAMPLE    The source of such a completion may be a customer order.

NOTE 1   The SpecificationInclusion is intended to complete the set of Specification objects for a BreakdownAssignment in order to enable the manufacturing of the product on the basis of an initial set of Specification objects defined.

NOTE 2   The following additional data can be assigned to a SpecificationInclusion: Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationInclusion.id
Description:

the identifier or set of identifiers for the SpecificationInclusion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in .

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationInclusion.description
Description:

the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SpecificationInclusion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationInclusion.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the SpecificationInclusion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationInclusion.ifCondition
Description:

the Specification or the SpecificationExpression that serves as the condition for the inclusion.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.SpecificationInclusion.includedSpecification
Description:

the Specification or the SpecificationExpression objects that are to be included. The includedSpecification shall not reference a SpecificationExpression with an operation of type 'or' or 'oneof', except for negating expressions, i.e., as participants in an expression preceded by a 'not' operator. Expressions of operator 'not' shall not be nested within one another.

In the case where more than one Specification is to be included a SpecificationExpression of type 'and' shall be used.

NOTE 4   In the case where the includedSpecification is a 'not' expression, the object actually defines an exclusion.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ViewContext
Description:

A ViewContext is a grouping of an application domain and a life cycle stage. It identifies a universe of discourse suitable for the description of parts.

NOTE    Requirements and vocabularies vary among the industrial activity fields. This entity intends to identify such domains.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ViewContext.description
Description:
the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ViewContext. The value of this attribute need not be specified.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ViewContext.applicationDomain
Description:

the identification of the applications for which an object may be relevant. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'assembly study': The object may be relevant for an assembly study;
  • 'digital mock-up': The object may be relevant for digital mock-up;
  • 'electrical design': The object may be relevant for the electrical design;
  • 'mechanical design': The object may be relevant for the mechanical design;
  • 'preliminary design': The object may be relevant for the preliminary design;
  • 'process planning': The object may be relevant for the process planning;
  • 'product support': The object may be relevant for the product support;
  • 'not specific': The object is considered as not specific of any application domain.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ViewContext.lifeCycleStage
Description:

the general stage in the product life cycle to which the concerned items belong. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'design': The concerned item belongs to the design phase of the life cycle;
  • 'manufacturing': The concerned item belongs to the manufacturing phase of the life cycle;
  • 'support': The concerned item belongs to the support phase of the life cycle;
  • 'recycling': The concerned item belongs to the recycling phase of the life cycle;
  • 'not specific': The object is considered as not specific of any life cycle stage.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.ViewContext.ur:UR1
Description:

The combination of the applicationDomain and the lifeCycleStage shall be unique.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkOrder.orderType
Description:

the orderType specifies the kind of the WorkOrder. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'design deviation permit': An authorization for a deviation from the approved design data;
  • 'design release': An authorization for the design of a product or of an item or to create a bill of material;
  • 'management resolution': An authorization by a committee, such as the board of directors, to design or change an item;
  • 'manufacturing release': An authorization for the manufacturing process of a product or of an item;
  • 'production deviation permit': An authorization for a deviation from the approved manufacturing process.

the identifier or set of identifiers for the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkRequest.classifiedAs
Description:

the classifications of the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkRequest.requestType
Description:

the intention of the WorkRequest. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'change of standard': A request to translate a change to a standard into action;
  • 'cost reduction': A request aimed at reducing the engineering and manufacturing costs of an item;
  • 'customer rejection': A request resulting from a rejection by a customer;
  • 'customer request': A request for an activity that is necessary to solve the request of a customer;
  • 'durability improvement': A request aimed at extending the life time of an item;
  • 'government regulation': A request resulting from legal requirements;
  • 'procurement alignment': A request to adjust the purchasing process of different items;
  • 'production alignment': A request to adjust the manufacturing process of different items;
  • 'production relief': A request aimed at achieving a simpler assembly and production process;
  • 'production requirement': A request for an activity that is necessary from a production point of view;
  • 'quality improvement': A request aimed at increasing the quality of an item;
  • 'security reason': A request for an activity that is necessary from a security point of view;
  • 'standardization': A request to unify variants of an item;
  • 'supplier request': A request for an activity necessary to solve the request of a supplier;
  • 'technical improvement': A request aimed at improving the technical aspects of an item;
  • 'tool improvement': A request aimed at increasing the useful life of a tool.
Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkRequest.notifiedPersons
Description:

the personnel that shall be informed about the WorkRequest and the date when the personnel or organization shall be informed. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Reference: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkRequest.requestor

the person or organization who issued the WorkRequest and the date when this person or organization issued the WorkRequest.
